title: Kossel Mini Flying extruder inc new E3D Titan Version

description.text: 4-5-16 - New version available for e3d titan extruder. This can be run (if you're using 1.75mm filament) from a 20mm "pancake" nema 17 so the total extruder and flying bracket is only 250g. The old version with a standard 40mm nema 17 and lightweight extruder was 395g! UPDATED - There are two carriages, one with the flying extruder loop fixed to it and standard belt clips. The other has quick release belt clips and moves the loop to fix on the top using the upper two bolts which hold the carriage onto the slides. Its only 2mm so the standard bolts should still work. I made a flying extruder for a Kossel Mini Delta printer. Replace the carriages with these parts and string them to the extruder mount with some elastic material, I am using sewing elastic at present, but apparently modelling balloons work or silicone straps etc... Allow just enough tension to hold the extruder mount up, with extruder attached, centred between your three carriages. The additional parts to hold the elastic do make restringing the belts a little fiddly but I presume it's not something you are going to do very often. This has been designed for this extruder (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:275593) but the file is public on tinkercad so feel free to alter it to fit whatever extruder you have (https://tinkercad.com/things/dJ0MpmOgcXt). The editable version of the titan flying extruder bracket is here (https://www.tinkercad.com/things/jYfQ3kHzbqz-djdemond-kossel-flying-extruder-e3d-titan-version). Aim to send the filament straight down the centre of the mount to the effector/hot end. In the photo the version I printed has my initials in the centre of the mount as a weight saving device and path for the filament to use, but in this version I have just left a large hole which should allow the filament path to be unhindered whatever extruder you are using. Attach the extruder to the effector/hot end with a bowden tube, which will now be somewhere between 4-6 times shorter than it was before, giving you hugely improved filament control, and adjust your retraction settings to be a little less aggressive I am now using 2mm at 150mm/s instead of 5mm at 100 mm/s. UPDATED - A small amount of downwards tension on the bowden tube helps so its not too long - too much bouncing around of flying extruder, or too short - too much tension on the elastics. Despite this setup and the extruder now adding considerable mass to the carriages this is only fully affects the inertia of z direction moves and not in a way that seems to affect print quality, x and y direction moves are only marginally affected as the mount can swivel around relatively freely, so don't overdo the elastics, or have too short a bowden tube. Might be worth reducing your acceleration and xy jerk by 10% if it seems to be causing your corners to print less well than before. Update 02-06-16 I recently changed to an effector where most of the hot end is above the effector. As such the bowden tube using the titan flying bracket was too short to be flexible enough to function, so I made an inverted version for putting the extruder above the flying bracket to allow a slightly longer tube.

This 3d model is a board that can be used to teach people braille. All of the letters of the alphabet are on this board.

Objectives This model should teach both blind and regular people how to read braille in a simple way. Audiences The intended audience is anyone who has a sense of touch. Both blind people and regular people can easily learn the braille alphabet through this model. Preparation You need little to no experience to use this learning tool, only a 3d printer to print it! Steps To read the braille, place your finger on the first set of dots. You should feel only one dot under your finger, representing the letter A. To go to the next letter by sliding your finger over to the next set of dots. Once you have gone through the first 13 letters, move down a row and restart the process again on the letter N. Results Students should have printed a easy to use braille alphabet board. This board should teach them how to read all of the letters of the braille alphabet. A suggested grading assignment would be to have the student randomly touch one of the letters and have them tell you which letter that is.

title: Leapfrog Creatr Fan Plate and Fan Mount

description.text:
This is a replacement part for the Leapfrog Creatr 3D printer. This is the inside plate located on the extruder carriage, just inside the fans.
There are some improvements as well. First, the duct holes are 100% open which provide better cooling for the filament before entering the extruder. Second, the mount for the electrical harness belt is higher which removes any concerns about snagged wires or filament. Third, there is an additional mount on the right side which allows one of the fans to be relocated to blow air underneath the extruder carriage.
This fan mount attaches to the Leapfrog Creatr Fan Plate, and moves one of the cooling fans outside of the extruder carriage. The fan is relocated to blow air across the bottom of the extruder carriage and the extruder heads.
The improvements make a huge difference in print quality. In addition, the Leapfrog Creatr is now able to print far more filament types.
TIP: Print this with STRONG plastic as there is some torque being applied to the plate via the electrical harness belt.

I've made this fancy soap holder. It has a nice flat base with lots of rounded edges. All in between are holes for the soapy water to flow out. I first created a nice rounded soap holder body in openSCAD. Then, I wrote a simple python script to implement a circle packing algorithm into the shape of the soap holder. This program packed in the various size holes as closely as it could, and exported the data into a format that openSCAD could read. Feel free to play around with the script and make your own randomized designs. The inspiration definitely goes to Art Lebedev: http://www.artlebedev.com/everything/saponius/

My printer is currently out of commission, and I hope to have it working within a few weeks! For now, please slice the model and let me know if it works on your machine. It should make for a really stylish soap holder, that's for sure :)

title: Removable Folding Spool Arm for Lulzbot Mini

description.text:
When we built the enclosure for our Lulzbot Mini 3D printer, we needed to replace the stock pivoting spool holder, so we designed a bracket to mount a removable spool arm. The first version was just a hack (literally - we hack sawed the bottom off the stock arm, and made it removable, with the printable bracket we designed. We also made a printable version of this where we hacked off the bottom in OpenSCAD. But we were never really happy with that solution, so here is an improved spool arm. This one uses the same bracket, as the old hack, but it changes the upper end to pivot and fold up for storage. We're really please with the final product. And, it is still printable, and we made it sow that both pieces fit on the build platform of the Lulzbot Mini. (the stock arm did not.) Now you can print your own removable-folding spool arm. This project is part of our effort to improve our enclosure kit for the Lulzbot Mini. If your're interested, the kit is available at: https://www.tabsynth.com/product/enclosure-for-lulzbot-mini-3d-printer/ Compatible with our Right Side Enclosure Panel (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2094867) Enjoy,
Jim Rasmussen

title: Funnel for 2 liter great for Filastruder / Filabot

description.text:
1/7/2016
I added the STL files of the funnel with male threads for those who would like to use it straight on to their filastruder, as well as an optional coupler so you can use that same funnel put the coupler on it and use it like my modified one without printing out 2.
Thanks goes to;
MrWhat - Creator of the PET Soda Bottle Coupler http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:897760
Emancipator - Creator of the hopper adapter http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:890734 I took the funnel which I really liked, but wasn't going to work for my application, however I like the original idea of the funnel adapter that emancipator designed!
I removed the inner wall, made it easier to print, and less plastic/print time.
Added the coupler from the other source PET Soda Bottle Coupler and made a threaded funnel! So this way you can use the 2 liter bottles, fill them up with 2lbs and colorant, and cap them. Makes it much easier to fill the 2 liter bottles, and then you can tumble and shake to mix. You can then store them and if you like put desiccant bags in the 2 liter bottles until ready to use (working on an o-ring cap with a hook to attach a string to hold the desiccant or a cap that has a skinny cylinder to fit down the neck of the 2 liter that holds the desiccant either loosely or in packets.

MakerBot

MakerBot Replicator 2X

Notes: Obviously you want to print with the wide top down as oriented in the stl file.

Took the funnel that "Emancipator" designed and removed the inner funnel area. Then took the coupler that MrWhat made, cut it in half and spliced them together. PRESTO, you have a threaded funnel!
I use this to fill 2 liter or even 1 liter bottles and works great.
Even has a second purpose, though it takes a little more time and is more tedious. If you want to separate colorant example if you added too much, the funnel holds a great static charge and attracts the colorant really well allowing the pla pellets to go down (I have only used this with balls of PLA from os3dp. It may not work with other non round pellets. It allowed me to successfully poor the bottles back and forth from one to the other and dump out the colorant that attracted to the funnel.. A lot better than pulling it out by hand lol.

description.text:
Vehicle's cupholders are sized to hold todays large drink cups.
That leaves your typical energy-drink-sized can vulnerable to tipping when cornering or decelerating (or accelerating if you're in a Tesla) rapidly.
This is my solution.  A cupholder sleeve that has an inner diameter to match the small can size.
There are two sizes; a short and tall.  In a Toyota Tundra, the front-most console cupholder is slightly tucked under the center dash, and shallower than the others, so the taller sleeve cannot be used there.  In the "main" cupholder, the taller sleeve is the same depth as the cupholder.
The holes are simply decorative, save plastic, and provide finger-grips to easily remove.

title: Floppy Leg Bracer for Mini Tripods

description.text:
I saw that some people were getting floppy leg syndrome on their Mini Tripods. I printed a Mini Tripod in PLA first, and it worked like a charm. I printed it in flexible TPU next for extra strength. 
I found that the flexible filament is very easy to snap apart after printing. This made it easy to unfold the legs and even have them be removable to replace with a different color if I so choose. Unfortunately, the legs were too unrestrained and became floppy. 
I made some sort of retaining collar the keep those pesky legs from doing the splits while wearing an expensive piece of hardware on top. Mine is flexible and it works perfectly. I think it should work a little better printed in a more rigid material, but I really wanted to keep the color scheme intact.
This should be a simple modification. Just place it between the ball head and legs and presto! You're done.

It’s designed to hold a number of gadgets that normally take up desktop space, but are now nicely integrated into a behind-my-monitor bracket. It holds two remote controls (one for the monitor and one for the Amazon Echo in the other room), a Vornado Flippi V remote control, a remote for the weird, new Apple TV remote control, and provides a powered dock/charger for the VXi BlueParrott B350-XT Bluetooth headset. While you're unlikely to have the same combination of items, you might be able to make use of some of the individual components and craft your own elements for any custom devices you use. The project uses a pin system to allow for printing with no supports, which worked out relatively well, but provided its own challenges. For more details, see the YouTube video and my article on ZDNet.

Assembly Assembly proved to be more of a challenge than I expected. The pins are very difficult to insert, but they provide added support. I found a combination of clamping, hammering, and judicious use of pliers helped. If you don't want to go through that effort and are willing to accept slightly less of a friction hold, consider resizing the pins to 4.25mm or 4.00mm. I printed this out in PLA and used superglue to help increase the robustness of the parts connections.

description.text:
Inspired by the Markus Raetz Yes No sculpture, and the Mojoptix digital sundial, I whipped up this customizable OpenSCAD script to take the intersection of two text extrusions. These are very difficult to print, without care. Any support whatsoever and you will have a very hard time getting it out of all the crevices. You will want to use dual extruders with dissolvable support. Just browsing through some of the remixes people have published using Customizer, I can see that some are impossible, and many are dubious. Good luck! For best results, stick to all capital letters, and letters which do not require support.
These letters are fine: AHIKLMNVWXY
These may work: BDJOQRU
The rest are problematic: CEFGPSTZ Lowercase letters are hard, because they have a lot more overhangs, they have descenders which will not appear, and they can have disconnected floating bits, like the dot of an "i". If you mix uppercase and lowercase, an uppercase letter in one direction may have parts that do not intersect anything in the other direction. You can have different text for the two viewing directions, adjust the angle between the views, and change the base thickness. The customizer isn't showing an option for changing the font parameter, I don't know why. In any case, I do not know what fonts the Customizer supports. If you wish to change the font, download the script and process it with OpenSCAD. Also be aware that the version in Customizer doesn't appear to be using the specified font; the middle point of the "M" does not touch the baseline, making it a hard to print letter, compared to the version in my photo.

description.text: Improved z axis precision by means of a 1:3 gearing. Moves the stepper from the bottom of the printer to the top. Thus, some adjustments have to be made. See instructions below!
The stock M8 screw might not be long enough for this part to fit to your printer!

Adjustment settings for the new Z-axis ratio These are instructions for the stock Marlin firmware shipped with the K8200:
  • you need to swap two of the four phases of the z-stepper to reverse the rotation:
    • swap pins 1 & 2 or 3 & 4 of the z-stepper connector on the controller board
    • do not swap pins 2 & 3 or 1 & 4 as this will not work
  • depending on which z-arbor you have (vanilla M8x1.25 or improved TR8x1.5) change the following z-steps per mm settings (Marlin g-code):
    1. change stepping:
      • for M8x1.25 => 7680 steps per mm z-lift: M92 Z7680.00
      • for TR8x1.5 => 6400 steps per mm z-lift: M92 Z6400.00
    2. store in EEPROM
      • M500
    3. Test these settings!
      • check whether Z moves into the correct direction
      • if Z moves into the wrong direction, manually press the Z-stop button to emergency stop it!
      • check whether Z moves the correct distance
      • placing a digital calipper between the z-arm and the top frame crossbeam and zeroing it in place should work just fine but be careful not to drive Z into the limits of the calipper!
      • check whether homing Z still works; you shouldn't need to readjust Z axis.
    • Other things to note... You likely need to extend the z-stepper cable... but I guess since you've already successfully built that K8200 printer you should be able to do this without any further instructions. Oh, I forgot to mention: it requires the Z-arbor to stick out long enough at the top of the printer. With the stock M8 screw this might not work. Since I have replaced it with a TR8x1.5 of 500mm length, what sticks out at the top is more than enough to mount the large cog to the screw.

The temple earpieces on my Eddie Bauer 8340 eyeglasses broke off after a very short time. Seeing that the hinge/strain relief had a grievous design error, I opted to design and print my own replacements. I included two versions; I printed the flat-faced version and observed that they open out a little too much. Therefore, I canted the interface surface to slant them in a bit. The files with canted bits are *_Ang.stl

Notes: This is a workhorse piece, so they need to be relatively solid. I used 75% infill with 6 shells. The high shell count ensures the functional part that sees the most stress is solid.
I used rafts for the prints, but they are not needed; if you want a very smooth finish on the outside, you will want to print directly on polyimide (Kapton) tape.

Sand off stray pieces and errors.  Seal them and make them shiny with a dip in acetone or thin slurry; be careful not to fill the screw holes.  Alternately, use the vapor smoothing method.  For all of the solvent smoothing methods, be sure they are completely "dry" of the solvent before proceeding.  Once you have the finish you desire, dip them in boiling water to soften the plastic and carefully work a bend into them to fit your face.  I fitted them with extra long screws and had to drill out the screw holes in the glasses a tiny bit to make them fit.
Update: I re-printed with no rafts 4 shells, and used vapor smoothing.  It came out very well; I could have let it smooth longer, but preferred a little of the print texture.  I consider it one of my better examples for why I am into 3D design and printing.
I used Autodesk 123D Design to model and Makerware desktop to slice.

This excellent stable camera platform is ideal for allround use and stable shots. In tripot configuration it is perfectly suitable for bumpy cars etc... It is also possible to change your tripod configuration into a single hand held device. I have created this gyroscopical camera holder for making movies at school and our next big school project. In our class they are amazed about how these simple physics keep a camera so stable. I hope many people will enjoy my design. 
Tags: #MakerEdChallenge , #ArtProject , #DesignProject , #EngineeringProject

Objectives: Due to problems we had in the past with shaky and unbalanced moving shots for our movies, I had the idea to design a lasting and simple camera platform. My results have been very good so far. Because it is an reliable and straight forward design my classmates get allong very well with it. My classmates have also been using it and if my printer feels like giving me a descent result I will make another one. And that one i'll give permanently to my school for future projects and next generations of students. Audiences: I am 17years old and a student doing architecture and design. But due to the simple and straight foreward design it can be given to children like my little sisters (who are 9). and get quite good results to. (they see it more as a toy and run around with it but that is why I made it so rugged) --) so it is sister proof. Preparation: We didn't have a lot of options before my gyro but a classmate took a long stick and put his camera on the end of it with some tape. But is was quite dangerous for the camera and so our teacher told us to stop with it. Steps: 1) download and print part one of the gyro
  • everything is quite straight foreward and schould be no problem to assemble
    (note). the long straw with a diameter off 1mm has to be sanded down to fit in . the tiny holes that allow you to pivot the gyro. also sand down the rest . of the joints to get a minimal desired friction between them.
    2) download and print part two of the gyro
  • the big cilinder is a grip to put on the gyro itself. (turning it into a hand held . device)
  • the long tube is the axle to put trough the middle of the gyro
    (note). DO NOT GLUE this part down IF you want an shock absorber
  • the remaining parts are a shock absorber put it over the main axle and put a . cople of springs in the case glue the case together and the top lid to the . main axle
  • have fun
    • Results: I realy hope some clever minds will update and improve this general design Tags: #MakerEdChallenge , #ArtProject , #DesignProject , #EngineeringProject

description.text:
Should work for any knife that is pointy at the end. May not work for squared off ends like a big meat cleaver because the sheath end is rounded off.  
NOTE: New version coming soon that provides optional decorations on the sheath! FOLLOW me to be sure not to miss it.  
There is an optional "window" cut out near the end of the knife. This window allows you to tell if the knife is serrated and has the shape you are looking for without unsheathing it. But be careful that when you insert the knife that your fingers are not gripping through the window. (Ouch!) If you think that's unsafe, there is an option to leave out the window and make the entire sheath solid.  
The script rotates the sheath 45 degrees. This makes it print diagonally, allowing a longer sheath to be printed, since the diagonal is the longest dimension of your printer. On my 3D touch (10" x 10" platen) I can actually print a 14" sheath by rotating this way.

Just feed in the length, maximum width, and thickness of the blade (in mm) into customizer to generate a custom knife sheath.   
The maximum width may be near the handle or may be near the tip depending on the style of blade, so measure carefully. I usually add another 1 to 2 mm extra to the width and length, and a quarter mm extra on the thickness. Maximum thickness is usually near the handle.   
2 mm works well as the blade thickness for typical medium sized kitchen knives. I had a small paring knife that required 1.5mm to make a snug fit. Calipers are helpful here. On my printer I found it was perfect to make the thickness about a quarter mm bigger than the caliper readings of the thickest part of the blade (usually near the handle).  
If you print one of these and find it is too loose to retain the knife, and you don't feel like wasting plastic by reprinting it with a smaller thickness, here is a trick:  Use a butane torch or even just a lighter to heat up the sheath near the opening where the knife is inserted, then when soft press it down with a cloth for a little while until it hardens. You can use this method to make the sheath looser or tighter so you get just the perfect amount of retention without having to struggle to insert the knife.
